        std::sort(temp2.begin(), temp2.end(), std::greater<int>());
        for (int j = i; j >= 0; j--) {
            for (int t = 0; t < temp2.size(); t++) {
                int idx = std::lower_bound(temp1.begin(), temp1.end(), temp2[t]) - temp1.begin();
                if (idx!= -1 && t < temp2.size()-1 && nums[idx] > nums[i]) {
                    res += temp2[t] - t - 1;
                }
                temp1.insert(temp1.begin() + idx, temp2[t]);
            }
            temp1.clear();
            std::copy(temp2.begin(), temp2.end(), temp1.begin());
        }
    }

    return res;
}
```

### Code Explanation

This solution uses a three-pointer technique to solve the problem. We first sort both the ascending order and descending order of the array and store the results in the `index1` and `index2` vectors. Then, we iterate through the `index1` and `index2` vectors, we first sort both vectors and then use the `std::lower_bound` function to get the index of the current element in `index1` (which is greater than the current element in `index2`) and update the `index2` vector based on the `index` of the current element in `index1`.  We also use dynamic array modification to sort `index2` in descending order.

For every element in `nums` at `i` index, we use a `std::vector<std::vector<int>>` called `temp1` and `temp2` which contain both sorted index1 and index2 respectively and then use the three pointer technique to count the number of indices `j` where index in `temp1` is less than index in `temp2` and nums at index `j` is greater than `nums[i]`  So, we increment the count res, each time we pass through the `i` index we update both temp1 and temp2 which will be used in next iteration for sorting and update the res.

### Time Complexity

The time complexity is O(n^2) because of the three-pointer technique used to sort the `index1` and `index2` vectors. In each iteration, we iterate through the `temp1` and `temp2` vectors and compare the current element in `nums` with its corresponding element in `temp1` and `temp2` which is O(n), where n is the size of `nums` array. In the worst case, when all elements in `nums` array are same, the time complexity can be calculated as O(n^2).

### Space Complexity

The space complexity is O(n^2) as we are using two vectors to store both sorted `index1` and `index2` vectors.

